    content: 'The global transition to renewable energy sources has accelerated dramatically over the past decade. Solar photovoltaic capacity has increased by over 300% since 2015, while wind energy capacity has more than doubled. This growth has been driven primarily by declining costs: the levelized cost of solar energy has fallen by 90% since 2010, making it cheaper than coal and natural gas in most markets. However, renewable energy faces significant challenges. Grid integration remains problematic because solar and wind power are intermittent—the sun does not always shine, and the wind does not always blow. Energy storage solutions, particularly battery technology, have improved substantially but remain expensive at utility scale. Additionally, the infrastructure for transmitting electricity from renewable-rich areas to population centers is often inadequate. Despite these challenges, many experts project that renewables will account for over 60% of global electricity generation by 2035, up from approximately 28% today. Policy frameworks, including carbon pricing and renewable portfolio standards, have been instrumental in accelerating this transition.',
