    id: 'p27',
    title: 'Cognitive Biases in Decision Making',
    content: 'Cognitive biases are systematic patterns of deviation from rationality in judgment. Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky identified numerous biases that affect human decision-making. The availability heuristic, for instance, causes people to overestimate the likelihood of events that are easily recalled, such as dramatic accidents versus common but less memorable causes of death. Confirmation bias leads individuals to seek out information that confirms their existing beliefs while ignoring contradictory evidence. The anchoring effect occurs when people rely too heavily on an initial piece of information when making subsequent judgments. These biases have significant practical implications. In medicine, diagnostic errors can result from anchoring on an initial diagnosis. In finance, investors may exhibit herd behavior driven by availability cascades. In the legal system, eyewitness testimony is notoriously unreliable due to memory biases. Behavioral economists have shown that awareness of these biases alone is insufficient to overcome them; structural interventions, such as default options and choice architecture, are often necessary to improve decision-making outcomes.',
