    id: 'p28',
    title: 'The Rise of Ancient Greek Democracy',
    content: 'Athenian democracy emerged around 508 BCE under the leadership of Cleisthenes, who implemented a series of reforms that distributed political power more broadly among citizens. Unlike modern representative democracies, Athens practiced direct democracy, wherein citizens voted directly on legislation and executive decisions. The central institution was the Ekklesia (Assembly), which met approximately forty times per year and required a quorum of 6,000 citizens. Any citizen could speak and propose legislation, though in practice, a class of professional politicians known as demagogues often dominated proceedings. The Boule, a council of 500 citizens chosen by lot, prepared legislation for the Assembly. This system of sortition—selecting officials by lottery—was considered more democratic than elections, which Athenians viewed as favoring the wealthy and aristocratic. Athenian democracy had significant limitations. Women, slaves, and metics (resident aliens) were excluded from political participation, meaning only about 10-20% of the population could vote. Critics such as Plato and Aristotle were skeptical of democracy, arguing that it enabled demagogues to manipulate public opinion. Despite these limitations, the Athenian experiment in direct democracy profoundly influenced subsequent political thought and remains a touchstone for democratic theory.',
