    title: 'Natural Selection and Evolutionary Theory',
    content: 'Darwin\'s theory of evolution by natural selection revolutionized biology by providing a mechanistic explanation for the diversity of life. The theory rests on three observable premises: organisms produce more offspring than can survive, individuals within a population vary in heritable traits, and environmental resources are limited. Given these conditions, individuals with traits better suited to their environment are more likely to survive and reproduce, passing those advantageous traits to subsequent generations. Over time, this process leads to the accumulation of adaptive characteristics and can ultimately result in speciation. The modern synthesis of the early twentieth century reconciled Darwinian evolution with Mendelian genetics, establishing that random mutations provide the raw material upon which natural selection acts, and that population genetics governs the dynamics of evolutionary change. Contemporary evolutionary biology has expanded well beyond the modern synthesis to incorporate insights from genomics, developmental biology, and ecology. The discovery of horizontal gene transfer, particularly among prokaryotes, has complicated the traditional tree-of-life model by revealing extensive genetic exchange across lineages. Research on epigenetics has demonstrated that environmentally induced modifications to gene expression can sometimes be inherited across generations, blurring the boundary between genetic and environmental influences. Neutral theory challenges the assumption that most evolutionary changes are driven by selection, arguing that many genetic changes are fixed by random drift rather than adaptive advantage. Despite these ongoing refinements, natural selection remains the cornerstone of evolutionary explanation.',
