    title: 'Behavioral Economics and Decision Making',
    content: 'Traditional economic theory rests on the assumption that human beings are rational actors who make decisions by weighing costs and benefits to maximize utility. Behavioral economics challenges this assumption by incorporating insights from psychology to understand how people actually decide. Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky\'s prospect theory demonstrates that individuals exhibit loss aversion, feeling the pain of losses more intensely than the pleasure of equivalent gains. This asymmetry leads to decisions that violate standard economic predictions, such as holding losing investments too long while selling winning investments too quickly. Framing effects further illustrate deviations from rationality: people respond differently to a medical treatment described as having a ninety percent survival rate than to one described as having a ten percent mortality rate, even though the statistics are identical. The endowment effect describes the tendency for people to value items they own more highly than identical items they do not own, leading to reluctance to trade. Nudge theory, popularized by Richard Thaler and Cass Sunstein, proposes that policymakers can improve outcomes by designing choice architectures that steer individuals toward better decisions without restricting freedom. Examples include automatically enrolling employees in retirement savings plans with opt-out provisions, which dramatically increases participation compared to opt-in systems. Critics argue that nudges may be manipulative, but proponents counter that choices are inevitably presented in some context and that well-designed defaults benefit both individuals and society.',
