    id: 'p19',
    title: 'The Socratic Method and Philosophy',
    content: 'Socrates, the Athenian philosopher who lived from approximately 470 to 399 BCE, developed a method of philosophical inquiry that has profoundly influenced Western thought. The Socratic method involves a cooperative dialogue in which a questioner poses questions designed to expose contradictions in the interlocutor\'s beliefs, leading to refined understanding or recognition of ignorance. Socrates himself wrote nothing; our knowledge comes primarily from Plato\'s early dialogues. In these dialogues, Socrates typically begins by professing ignorance and asking his interlocutor to define a concept such as justice, piety, or courage. Through persistent questioning, he reveals that the initial definition is inadequate or inconsistent with other beliefs held by the interlocutor. The goal is not to win an argument but to clear away false certainty and create conditions for genuine understanding. This emphasis on intellectual humility, encapsulated in Socrates\'s famous assertion that he knows nothing, represents a radical departure from the Sophists, who taught rhetoric as a means of persuasion regardless of truth. Plato\'s own philosophical development moved beyond the primarily negative approach of the early Socratic dialogues toward the positive metaphysical system of his middle works, particularly the theory of Forms. Yet the Socratic method has remained influential as a pedagogical technique and model of critical thinking, emphasizing rigorous examination of assumptions and logical consistency. Modern education continues to employ Socratic questioning in law schools and other settings where analytical reasoning is paramount, demonstrating the enduring relevance of this ancient practice.',
    source: 'Princeton Review',
    difficulty: 'medium',
    questions: ['q_verbal_155', 'q_verbal_156', 'q_verbal_157'],
    wordCount: 350,
